flowRoot.flowPara: Streamer Zone: The ionization processes associated with the formation and propagation of each single streamer is the source of the electrical current for heating the leader head/channel.
Leader Head (Stem): The initiation point of the streamers inside the streamer zone, each carrying a low current and the transition region where cold streamers form into a hot leader channel.
Leader Channel: Hot plasma filament at temperature of 5,000+ K. Highly conductive and capable of carrying the transmitting the electrode potential to the leader head.
Streamer Front: High space charge field. Electron-impact ionization is the dominant source fed from pre-ionization region electrons formed via photoionization..
Although positive and negative leaders exhibit differing characteristics, the streamer-to-leader transition (or air heating) is the fundamental process that allows leaders to propagate.
